abstract: Dave DeBusschere, Hall of Fame forward who helped propel New York Knicks to their only two NBA championships, dies at age 62 after suffering heart attack on Manhattan street; 12-season NBA career recalled; photo (M)
snippet: Dave DeBusschere, Hall of Fame forward who helped propel New York Knicks to their only two NBA championships, dies at age 62 after suffering heart attack on Manhattan street; 12-season NBA career recalled; photo (M)
lead_paragraph: Dave DeBusschere, the Hall of Fame forward whose tenacious defensive play, rebounding prowess and timely scoring helped propel the Knicks to their only two N.B.A. championships, died yesterday in Manhattan. He was 62.
headline_main: Dave DeBusschere, 62, Relentless Forward On Knicks' Championship Teams, Is Dead
headline_print_headline: Dave DeBusschere, 62, Relentless Forward On Knicks' Championship Teams, Is Dead

abstract: Atlantic Coast Conference annual spring meeting produces no result on its own expansion, but Big East Conference will reportedly fight to keep Miami University from moving to ACC (M)
snippet: Atlantic Coast Conference annual spring meeting produces no result on its own expansion, but Big East Conference will reportedly fight to keep Miami University from moving to ACC (M)
lead_paragraph: The university presidents of the Atlantic Coast Conference moved closer to expanding the league to 12 teams from 9 today at the conference's annual spring meeting, the first splash in what could be a tidal wave of change in college athletics.
headline_main: A.C.C. Nears Expansion, and Big East Nears a Breakup

abstract: Following is an accounting of the articles in which falsification, plagiarism and similar problems were discovered in a review of articles written by Jayson Blair, a reporter for The New York Times who resigned May 1. The review, conducted by a team of Times reporters and researchers, concentrated on the 73 articles Mr. Blair wrote since late October, when he was given roving national assignments and began covering major news events including the Washington-area sniper attacks and the rescue of Pfc. Jessica D. Lynch. Spot checks of his previous stories also found errors of fact and possible fabrications.    Detective Says Sniper SuspectWas Interrogated After He Requested Lawyer  APRIL 29, 2003

abstract: CORRECTING THE RECORD; The Articles; Witnesses and Documents Unveil Deceptions In a Reporter's Work    On Sunday, May 11, 2003, The Times published a two-full-page accounting of misrepresentations and plagiarism by Jayson Blair, who resigned on May 1 as a reporter. This article was among those described. The description:    Fighting Words: Whose Icon Is It?  SEPT. 29, 2002    FACTUAL ERRORS -- In an article about the effort by some family members of passengers on one of the aircraft hijacked on Sept. 11, 2001, to trademark the phrase ''let's roll,'' Mr. Blair quoted John F. Delaney, a lawyer, on what a trademark is. Mr. Blair quoted Mr. Delaney accurately but failed to identify him or his law firm correctly. Mr. Delaney's first name is John, not Jonathan, and he is a lawyer in the New York office of Morrison & Foerster, not Morrison & Forester.
lead_paragraph: CORRECTING THE RECORD; The Articles; Witnesses and Documents Unveil Deceptions In a Reporter's Work

abstract: A selective listing by critics of The Times of noteworthy pop and jazz concerts in the New York metropolitan region this weekend. * denotes a highly recommended concert.    JANN ARDEN, Upstairs at Studio 54, 254 West 54th Street, Manhattan, (212) 445-0190. The Canadian songwriter Jann Arden's affectionate folk-pop has found a place on movie soundtracks and television shows like ''Dawson's Creek.'' For her first New York shows in seven years, she's playing a weeklong engagement that is being filmed for Canadian television. Tonight and tomorrow night at 8; tickets are $37.50 in advance, $40 on the day of the show (Jon Pareles).

Profile of Tottenville neighborhood of Staten Island, New York, from point of view of prospective resident; photos; map (M)
snippet: Profile of Tottenville neighborhood of Staten Island, New York, from point of view of prospective resident; photos; map (M)
lead_paragraph: IN the late 1990's, Marilyn Blohm and her husband, John, were living the bucolic life on a street that ran through a patch of protected Staten Island woods called the Clay Pit Ponds State Park Preserve. It was quiet and green, safe for their two young sons and a happy haven for the family dogs. When it came time to move to a neighborhood with more children for their sons to play with, they found the perfect house nearby in Tottenville.
